# This is the EXAMPLE/TEMPLATE copy -- committed to git, same idea as .env.example. Copy this file
# to profiles.yaml (repo root, alongside docker-compose.yml) and fill in your own chat_path/
# prompts/defaults -- that copy is gitignored (never committed), since it's real per-deployment
# config, not something to share. docker-compose.yml bind-mounts profiles.yaml (not this file)
# straight into the ingest-worker container (at /app/profiles.yaml, the same path
# AI_STAGE_PROFILE_PATH already defaults to), so editing your real copy and restarting the
# container is enough; no image rebuild needed. frigate/ingest-worker/profiles.yaml is a separate
# copy baked into the image as the fallback default (used only if the bind mount is ever removed).
#
# Configures both internal AI stages -- ai_worker.py (ai_events_stage_enabled below) and
# alert_ai_worker.py (ai_alerts_enabled below), the only AI-stage implementation in this project
# now (n8n/metadata-processor.json was deleted as stale -- it never moved past the old
# vehicle_sightings/person_sightings shape this project moved away from -- see CLAUDE.md's
# "Universal sightings" / "Internal AI stage" sections).
#
# object_types is FLAT and universal -- one entry per Frigate object label (raw_events.objects),
# each with its own prompt/model. There is no "sighting_type" concept in the code at all: every
# analyzed sighting (car, truck, person, dog, whatever you add here) is stored the exact same way
# (see db.complete_sighting/complete_visit_sighting) -- the label itself is just data on the row
# (object_label), not a branch in the code. A Frigate label with no entry here is simply never
# claimed by either stage at all -- ai_status (or alert_ai_status) stays 'new' indefinitely,
# exactly as if that stage were off for that one type. Not a bug to fix -- there's nothing
# configured for it yet, add an entry whenever you want one analyzed.
#
# Two prompts per entry, for two genuinely different inputs:
#   event_prompt -- ai_worker.py sends this with ONE single-frame crop (the raw_event's own
#     region/box, or Frigate's own snapshot when frigate_snapshot_enabled is true). Framed for a
#     single static moment.
#   alert_prompt -- alert_ai_worker.py sends this with the visit's own composite grid (4 frames
#     sampled across the visit's whole span). Framed for both a confident static read (using
#     whichever of the 4 panels shows a detail most clearly) AND a description of what changed
#     across the sequence, in the SAME flowing answer -- there's no separate structured field for
#     "what changed," the prompt just asks for both together, same shape person's prompt already
#     used before this file went universal.
# Both prompts are answered as plain free text (no JSON) -- the whole response becomes
# sightings.description/visit_sightings.description verbatim. This is deliberate: a fixed JSON
# schema is exactly the kind of per-type structure this redesign removed. If you want a detail
# captured (plate text, breed, collar color, whatever), ask for it directly in the prompt's own
# wording -- the model's own sentence is the record, not a set of columns.
#
# provider (optional, per type, default "llama_proxy") -- which backend ai_worker.py/
# alert_ai_worker.py call for THIS type's chat completion. Three values:
#   llama_proxy (default) -- your own locally-hosted model behind LLAMA_PROXY_BASE_URL (e.g.
#     llama_slot_proxy), selected via chat_path (below). Omitting `provider` entirely keeps this
#     the behavior -- an existing profiles.yaml with no `provider` key anywhere needs no edit.
#   openai -- OpenAI's own hosted API (OPENAI_BASE_URL/OPENAI_API_KEY in .env). Needs `model`
#     (below) instead of chat_path -- OpenAI selects the model via a body field, not a URL path.
#   anthropic -- Claude's Messages API (ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL/ANTHROPIC_API_KEY/ANTHROPIC_VERSION in
#     .env). Also needs `model`, plus takes an optional `max_tokens` (falls back to
#     AI_STAGE_DEFAULT_MAX_TOKENS, 1024, if omitted) -- Claude's API requires max_tokens on every
#     request, unlike the other two.
# This is a per-type choice, not a global one -- one type can stay on llama_proxy while another
# routes to Claude or OpenAI, in the same file, same as chat_path already lets you point different
# types at different local model slots. See CLAUDE.md's "Cloud VLM providers" section and
# docs/configuration.md's "Internal AI stages" section for a fuller explanation, including which
# provider tends to suit which kind of description task.
#
# chat_path is llama_proxy-only (ignored for openai/anthropic, which use `model` instead). model
# is required for openai/anthropic (ignored for llama_proxy, which selects the model via
# chat_path). Only set the one your chosen provider actually needs.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Three complete, mutually-exclusive shapes for wiring up ONE object type's chat call, shown
# side by side so it's clear exactly which keys travel together -- don't mix keys from two of
# these on the same entry. (event_prompt/alert_prompt omitted below for brevity; see the real
# values under object_types.car further down for what those actually look like.)
#
#   1) llama_proxy (the default) -- your own locally-hosted model, no `provider` key at all.
#      Despite the name, this shape works against ANY server that speaks an OpenAI-compatible
#      /v1/chat/completions API at LLAMA_PROXY_BASE_URL -- not only llama_slot_proxy:
#     car:
#       chat_path: /REPLACE_WITH_VEHICLE_SLOT/v1/chat/completions
#       timeout_seconds: 180
#
#      1a) Through llama_slot_proxy (multiple model slots behind one host, one URL path
#          segment per slot -- the shape above, and what this file's examples assume):
#            .env:  LLAMA_PROXY_BASE_URL=http://llama-proxy-host:port
#            here:  chat_path: /REPLACE_WITH_VEHICLE_SLOT/v1/chat/completions
#
#      1b) Direct to a bare llama.cpp server (`llama-server`), no proxy in front -- llama.cpp's
#          own server already speaks the identical OpenAI-compatible API, so chat_path is just
#          llama.cpp's real, fixed route (no per-slot path segment, since one llama-server
#          process only ever serves the one model it was started with):
#            .env:  LLAMA_PROXY_BASE_URL=http://llama-cpp-host:8080
#            here:  chat_path: /v1/chat/completions
#          Caveat: LLAMA_PROXY_BASE_URL is one global host (.env, not per-type) -- this shape is
#          clean when every type shares that one loaded model, or you only care about one type.
#          Routing different types to different *local* models without a proxy in front isn't
#          possible with this shape alone, since chat_path only varies the URL path, never the
#          host/port -- that per-type multiplexing is exactly what llama_slot_proxy (1a) is for.
#
#   2) openai -- OpenAI's hosted API, model selected via `model` (chat_path is unused/ignored):
#     car:
#       provider: openai
#       model: gpt-4o
#       timeout_seconds: 180
#
#   3) anthropic -- Claude's Messages API, model selected via `model`, plus an optional
#      max_tokens (Claude's API requires max_tokens on every request, unlike the other two):
#     car:
#       provider: anthropic
#       model: claude-opus-4-8
#       max_tokens: 1024   # optional; falls back to AI_STAGE_DEFAULT_MAX_TOKENS (1024) if omitted
#       timeout_seconds: 180
#
# object_types.car below actually uses shape 1 (llama_proxy) -- to route that one type to a
# hosted provider instead, swap its chat_path line for shape 2's or 3's keys.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Embeddings (semantic search) are configured separately from chat, via .env's EMBEDDING_PROVIDER
# (llama_proxy default, or openai) -- NOT here, and NOT per object type. This is because Claude has
# no embeddings API at all: a type routed to `provider: anthropic` for its chat/description call
# still needs EMBEDDING_PROVIDER set to llama_proxy (default) or openai for that same sighting's
# embedding to be computed. See docs/configuration.md's "Semantic search" section.
#
# A bunch of settings, ALL OPTIONAL, live entirely in this file -- see profile_config.py. These are
# NOT env vars at all (deliberately -- they're settings you'd realistically want different per
# Frigate object type, so this file is the one place to configure them, not split across .env and
# here). Two tiers, checked in this order: a type's own object_types.<label> entry (below), then the
# `defaults` section right below this comment (a common value applied to every type that doesn't
# set its own -- for "change this everywhere except one or two exceptions"). If NEITHER sets a
# given key, ingest-worker falls back to a hardcoded default matching this project's original
# behavior (see config.py) -- so an empty/missing `defaults:` section and no per-type overrides is
# a perfectly valid, fully-working configuration, not a half-finished one.
#   telegram_events_mode / telegram_alerts_mode -- none/image/video/all (see telegram.py). e.g. a
#     `dog` entry could set telegram_events_mode: none to silence noisy dog-only notifications
#     while cars/people still notify normally. Hardcoded fallback: "none" (both).
#   ai_events_stage_enabled / ai_alerts_enabled -- true/false, whether this project's only AI-stage
#     implementation analyzes this type (see CLAUDE.md's "Internal AI stage" section). Setting
#     either true for at least one type (or in `defaults`) is enough to start that stage's poll thread --
#     see profile_config.any_ai_events_stage_enabled/any_ai_alerts_enabled, used by main.py's
#     thread-startup check. Hardcoded fallback: false (both, i.e. off).
#   crop_disabled / crop_frame_offset_pct / crop_padding_pct / frigate_snapshot_enabled -- crop
#     framing for this type's own event crop. Resolved fresh for every event, since crop_worker
#     already processes every type regardless -- no queue/thread implications, just which image
#     ends up on the row. e.g. a `car` entry could set frigate_snapshot_enabled: false plus its own
#     crop_frame_offset_pct to use a seek-based crop with more control over framing for plate
#     legibility, while other types keep using Frigate's own snapshot. Hardcoded fallback:
#     crop_disabled=false, crop_frame_offset_pct=0.5, crop_padding_pct=0.2,
#     frigate_snapshot_enabled=true.
#   store_video / store_video_alerts / visit_thumb_crop_enabled -- true/false. Unlike the AI-stage
#     flags above, these apply to *any* Frigate label by default (not just ones with a
#     profiles.yaml prompt entry), so a type can get its own entry here purely to carry one of
#     these three keys, with no chat_path/prompt at all. Setting any of them true for at least one
#     type (or in `defaults`) is enough to start that stage's poll thread -- see
#     profile_config.any_store_video_enabled/any_store_video_alerts_enabled/
#     any_visit_thumb_crop_enabled. e.g. a `person` entry could set store_video: false to skip
#     storing clips for people while cars still get them. Hardcoded fallback: false (all three).
#   visit_preview_frame_percentages -- a real YAML list of exactly 4 numbers (0=clip start, 100=clip
#     end) -- which 4 points of a visit's own clip to sample for that type's composite grid/GIF.
#     e.g. a slow-moving `car` visit might want frames spread wider ([0, 30, 65, 100]) than a
#     `person` visit that's over quickly. Hardcoded fallback: [0, 25, 50, 100].
#
# `defaults:` ALSO holds a second, unrelated category: plain technical tuning knobs with no
# per-object-type meaning at all -- queue parallel limits, retry counts, timeouts, poll intervals,
# retention schedule. These can ONLY be set in `defaults:` (never per-type -- there's no
# "PARALLEL_LIMIT for cars only"), resolved once at startup by config.apply_profile_defaults(), not
# per-call like the per-type settings above. Every key below is optional; omit any of them to keep
# this project's original hardcoded default (shown after each), same "empty defaults: is a
# perfectly valid config" idea as above:
#   parallel_limit (2) / stale_minutes (5) / max_attempts (3) / crop_initial_wait_seconds (5) --
#     crop-stage queue tuning: how many events may be crop_status='processing' at once, how long
#     before a stuck claim is reclaimed, how many failures before giving up, how long to wait
#     before the first crop attempt on a freshly claimed row.
#   max_crop_dimension (1280) / thumbnail_max_dimension (240) -- image-size caps: the full crop's
#     long side (VLMs downsample beyond this anyway) and the much smaller copy used for
#     report/preview UIs.
#   poll_interval_seconds (5) -- how often the crop poll loop checks for new work.
#   retention_months (12) / retention_check_interval_seconds (86400) -- how long data is kept
#     before an automatic sweep deletes it, and how often that sweep runs.
#   video_parallel_limit (1) / video_initial_wait_seconds (10) / video_min_valid_bytes (1000) /
#     video_max_attempts (5) / video_retry_wait_seconds (5) / video_max_age_hours (null, no limit)
#     -- video-download queue tuning, shared by both the events (store_video) and alerts
#     (store_video_alerts) flows.
#   visit_thumb_crop_parallel_limit (1) / visit_thumb_crop_initial_wait_seconds (5) /
#     visit_thumb_crop_max_attempts (3) / visit_thumb_crop_retry_wait_seconds (5) -- visit
#     preview (composite grid/GIF) queue tuning.
#   ai_stage_parallel_limit (2) / ai_stage_stale_minutes (5) / ai_stage_max_attempts (3) /
#     ai_stage_max_age_hours (null, no limit) / ai_stage_poll_interval_seconds (5) -- internal
#     AI-stage queue tuning, shared between the events and alerts AI stages.
#   ai_stage_default_timeout_seconds (180) / ai_stage_embed_timeout_seconds (60) -- fallback
#     chat-completion/embedding-call timeouts for a type that doesn't set its own `timeout_seconds`.
#
# defaults: (optional overall) -- common per-type-setting values applied to every object type that
# doesn't set its own for that same key (sitting between the per-type overrides above and their
# hardcoded fallback), PLUS the sole location for the technical tuning knobs just described. Leave
# it out entirely (or omit individual keys) to fall straight through to the hardcoded fallback,
# exactly as if this section didn't exist. Every key below is fully optional -- this lists ALL of
# them at once (with each one's hardcoded fallback as the commented-out value) purely so the whole
# surface is visible in one place; a real deployment typically only sets the handful that actually
# differ from the fallback (see CLAUDE.md's "Per-object-type overrides" section for a real
# example -- one production deployment only needed ~11 of these).
# defaults:
#   # Per-object-type settings (also overridable per type below -- see object_types.car's own
#   # commented-out block for the identical list in that context).
#   telegram_events_mode: none
#   telegram_alerts_mode: none
#   ai_events_stage_enabled: false
#   ai_alerts_enabled: false
#   crop_disabled: false
#   crop_frame_offset_pct: 0.5
#   crop_padding_pct: 0.2
#   frigate_snapshot_enabled: true
#   store_video: false
#   store_video_alerts: false
#   visit_thumb_crop_enabled: false
#   visit_preview_frame_percentages: [0, 25, 50, 100]
#   # Plain technical tuning knobs -- defaults: ONLY, never per-type (see the block above).
#   parallel_limit: 2
#   stale_minutes: 5
#   max_attempts: 3
#   crop_initial_wait_seconds: 5
#   max_crop_dimension: 1280
#   thumbnail_max_dimension: 240
#   poll_interval_seconds: 5
#   retention_months: 12
#   retention_check_interval_seconds: 86400
#   video_parallel_limit: 1
#   video_initial_wait_seconds: 10
#   video_min_valid_bytes: 1000
#   video_max_attempts: 5
#   video_retry_wait_seconds: 5
#   video_max_age_hours: null   # null = no limit
#   visit_thumb_crop_parallel_limit: 1
#   visit_thumb_crop_initial_wait_seconds: 5
#   visit_thumb_crop_max_attempts: 3
#   visit_thumb_crop_retry_wait_seconds: 5
#   ai_stage_parallel_limit: 2
#   ai_stage_stale_minutes: 5
#   ai_stage_max_attempts: 3
#   ai_stage_max_age_hours: null   # null = no limit
#   ai_stage_poll_interval_seconds: 5
#   ai_stage_default_timeout_seconds: 180
#   ai_stage_embed_timeout_seconds: 60
object_types:
  car: &vehicle_profile
    chat_path: /REPLACE_WITH_VEHICLE_SLOT/v1/chat/completions
    # How long to wait for this type's chat completion, in seconds -- a local model on CPU/modest
    # GPU can genuinely take minutes. Falls back to AI_STAGE_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT_SECONDS if omitted.
    timeout_seconds: 180
    # This entry uses shape 1 (llama_proxy, the default) from the three-way provider comparison
    # near the top of this file -- swap the chat_path line above for shape 2's (openai) or
    # shape 3's (anthropic) keys to route THIS type to a hosted provider instead.
    #
    # Example overrides (commented out -- uncomment/edit to actually use). Left here as a
    # discoverable template rather than only described in prose above.
    # telegram_events_mode: image
    # telegram_alerts_mode: all
    # ai_events_stage_enabled: true
    # ai_alerts_enabled: true
    # crop_disabled: false
    # crop_frame_offset_pct: 0.5
    # crop_padding_pct: 0.2
    # frigate_snapshot_enabled: true
    # store_video: true
    # store_video_alerts: true
    # visit_thumb_crop_enabled: true
    # visit_preview_frame_percentages: [0, 25, 50, 100]
    event_prompt: >-
      This image shows a single moment from one vehicle sighting. In one or two short sentences,
      describe the vehicle's color, body type (sedan/suv/truck/van/pickup/minivan/etc.), make and
      model if you can identify them, any notable features (roof rack, ladder rack, trailer hitch,
      bike rack, tinted windows, decals or commercial branding, visible damage or rust, unusual
      color/wrap, aftermarket wheels), and the license plate text if it's visible and legible. If a
      detail isn't visible or you're not confident, simply omit it rather than guessing. Do not
      describe your process.
    alert_prompt: >-
      This image is a 2x2 grid of 4 frames of the SAME vehicle captured moments apart during one
      visit (not 4 different vehicles) -- use all 4 panels together for the most confident read,
      since a detail unclear in one panel (angle, glare, motion blur) may be legible in another,
      e.g. the plate. In one or two short sentences, describe the vehicle's color, body type, make
      and model if identifiable, notable features, the license plate text if visible/legible in
      any panel, and what changed or happened across the sequence (e.g. "pulled into the driveway
      and parked", "drove past left to right", "reversed out and left"). If a detail isn't
      visible, omit it. Do not mention that the image is a grid. Do not describe your process.
  truck: *vehicle_profile
  person:
    chat_path: /REPLACE_WITH_PERSON_SLOT/v1/chat/completions
    timeout_seconds: 180
    event_prompt: >-
      This image shows a single moment of one person. Describe their clothing colors and what
      they appear to be doing in this one frame, in one short sentence. No speculation about
      identity.
    alert_prompt: >-
      This image is a 2x2 grid of 4 frames of the SAME person captured moments apart during one
      visit (not 4 different people) -- use all 4 panels together, since a detail unclear in one
      may be visible in another. Describe this person's clothing colors (a static detail, most
      reliable from whichever panel shows it most clearly) and what they appear to be doing across
      the sequence -- e.g. walking toward the door, carrying something, getting in/out of a
      vehicle -- in one short sentence covering both. No speculation about identity. Do not
      mention that the image is a grid.
  # A fourth type, added purely by adding an entry here -- no schema/code change (see the
  # object_types comment at the top). Demonstrates a real per-type override in context: this one
  # deployment wants dog *event* notifications (a photo per sighting) even though every other type
  # stays silent on events via `defaults:` above -- everything else about dog inherits from
  # `defaults:` like car/truck/person do, since it sets no other key here.
  dog:
    chat_path: /REPLACE_WITH_VEHICLE_SLOT/v1/chat/completions
    timeout_seconds: 180
    telegram_events_mode: image
    event_prompt: >-
      This image shows a single moment of one dog. Describe their breed and what they appear to be
      doing in this one frame, in one short sentence. No speculation about identity.
    alert_prompt: >-
      This image is a 2x2 grid of 4 frames of the SAME dog captured moments apart during one visit
      (not 4 different dogs) -- use all 4 panels together, since a detail unclear in one may be
      visible in another. Describe this dog's breed (a static detail, most reliable from whichever
      panel shows it most clearly) and what they appear to be doing across the sequence -- e.g.
      walking toward the door, playing, being walked on a leash -- in one short sentence covering
      both. No speculation about identity. Do not mention that the image is a grid.
